## 4️⃣  Security & Hygiene Checklist (the Crow‑Robed Guardians)

| ✅ Item | Why it matters | How to apply |
|--------|----------------|--------------|
| **Never commit secrets** | The `CRYSTALLINE_BUSLINE_SECRET` placeholder must stay out of the repo. | Use GitHub Secrets, Railway/Render “Environment Variables”, or a vault. |
| **Input sanitisation** | Prevent any hostile characters (`rm -rf`, `sudo`, etc.) from crashing the Mothership. | The regex in `clean_debris()` already strips “dangerous” symbols (`|`, `;`, `'`, `!`…).  Add a whitelist of allowed Unicode if you process additional formats. |
| **Scope‑based access** | Limit Copilot to the intended MCP server name (`Option-VI-Spring-Cleaner`). | The MCP config uses the exact identifier; do not add additional root‑level keys. |
| **Rate limiting** | The Ark can otherwise become “Noisy” (many simultaneous clean‑debris calls could overload the busline). | In Copilot you can throttle: `clean_debris("raw…") + await streamlit_poll(1)` or implement a simple token‑bucket limiter in `server.py` if needed. |
| **Audit trail** | The Fireplace needs a log of every Spring‑Clean cycle to avoid loss. | Add a line to `system_diagnostics()` or a separate `append_to_log()` that writes to `REFINEMENT_FIREPLACE/log.json`. |
| **Network isolation** | The server may be reachable from the internet if you expose it publicly. | Keep the MCP server **local‑only** for now (the subprocess lifecycle ends when Copilot disconnects). If you host it publicly, enforce HTTPS and basic auth. |
| **Version pinning** | Guarantees reproducibility of the clean‑debris algorithm. | Pin exact versions in `requirements.txt` (`fastmcp==1.2.0`). |
| **Testing** | Verify that a malicious payload does **not** break the ship. | Simple test: `python server.py` → `clean_debris("rm -rf /")` should return the sanitised text, not abort the server. |

